{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583554"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:18:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:18:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11732"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11732"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4345"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112699"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4345"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11732"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94732"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1619"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"10061"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46227"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112699"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old girl attends the school cross country marathon. She reports a \u0022burning\u0022 sensation throughout her legs and thighs during the race.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following physiological processes explains the burning sensation reported in the patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gluconeogenesis producing glucose from lactate","Glycolysis converting glycogen to glucose","Anaerobic glycolysis converting pyruvate to lactic acid","Aerobic glycolysis converting pyruvate to lactic acid","Glycolysis converting FAD to FADH2"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaerobic glycolysis converting pyruvate to lactic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct answer. The burning sensation is most likely due to the build-up of lactic acid in the muscle tissue of her thighs and legs. This is a by-product of anaerobic glycolysis during periods of high-intensity, sustained exercise, resulting in the oxygen demand of the muscles not being met with the required oxygen supply or blood flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGluconeogenesis producing glucose from lactate\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Gluconeogenesis is the process of producing glucose from non-carbohydrate sources, including lactate, but this occurs primarily in the liver and kidneys, not in exercising muscle, and does not cause the burning sensation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycolysis converting glycogen to glucose\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Glycolysis is the conversion of glucose to pyruvate, not the conversion of glycogen to glucose. This process is known as glycogenolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAerobic glycolysis converting pyruvate to lactic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Aerobic glycolysis occurs in the presence of ample oxygen and leads to the formation of pyruvate, which is then funnelled into the Krebs cycle (TCA cycle), not converted to lactic acid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycolysis converting FAD to FADH2\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Glycolysis converts NAD+ to NADH, not FAD to FADH2. This reduction reaction occurs in the Krebs cycle (TCA cycle).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anaerobic glycolysis is performed in the increasing absence of oxygen supply versus demand leading to the conversion of pyruvate to lactic acid."],"references":["Felig P, Wahren J. Fuel homeostasis in exercise. N Engl J Med 1975; 293:1078.","Ess\u00e9n B. Intramuscular substrate utilization during prolonged exercise. Ann N Y Acad Sci 1977; 301:30."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94732"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11732"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94732"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-04T08:22:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-04T08:24:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4345"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112699"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71